Here’s a concise pattern using a trait object collection and async_trait.

- Assume a trait with an async method:
  use async_trait::async_trait;

  #[async_trait]
  pub trait Repository<K, M> {
      async fn load_indexes(&mut self) -> Result<(), String>;
      // other methods...
  }

- Store repositories in a map:
  use std::collections::HashMap;

  pub struct Store<K, M> {
      repos: HashMap<String, Box<dyn Repository<K, M> + Send>>,
  }

- Implement collection to load all indexes and return the requested repo:
  impl<K, M> Store<K, M> {
      pub async fn collection(&mut self, name: String) -> Result<&mut dyn Repository<K, M>, String> {
          // load indexes for all repos (or you could scope to desired ones)
          for r in self.repos.values_mut() {
              r.load_indexes().await.map_err(|e| e)?;
          }

          self.repos
              .get_mut(&name)
              .map(|r| r.as_mut())
              .ok_or_else(|| "repository not found".into())
      }
  }

Notes:
- Use async_trait to define async trait methods.
- If you only want to load indexes for the found repo, move the loop to just that repo.
- Adjust error types to your project (instead of String).

when I load the db from file I want to initialize the collections. But repo statement below gives me an error. 
 async fn initialize(&self) -> Result<()> {

        for (name, _) in self.collections {
            let repo = self.collection(name).await?;
        }
        Ok(())
    }

Key issue: initialize uses &self but collection requires &mut self, and you can’t mutably borrow across an await.

Fix (minimally): make initialize take &mut self and drop the repo each iteration.

async fn initialize(&mut self) -> Result<()> {
    for name in self.collections.keys().cloned() {
        let _repo = self.collection(name).await?;
        // use _repo if needed, then it drops here
    }
    Ok(())
}

Notes:
- You must own a mutable borrow to call collection, hence &mut self.
- Don’t keep the &mut dyn Repository across await points; drop it each loop iteration. 
- If you truly need to keep it, restructure (collect names first, then second loop to load).

Yes. Annotate the repo binding with the trait object type.

Example:

async fn initialize(&mut self) -> Result<()> {
    for name in self.collections.keys().cloned() {
        let repo: &mut dyn Repository<K, M> = self.collection(name).await?;
        // use repo if needed (then it drops here)
    }
    Ok(())
}

Notes:
- initialize must be &mut self because collection requires &mut self.
- The repo binding is an explicit type: &mut dyn Repository<K, M>.
- Dropping each loop iteration avoids holding a mutable borrow across await.

You’re using K and M, but initialize must be inside a scope where K, M are in scope.

Fix: implement initialize on an impl that has K, M in scope (i.e., the struct is generic over K, M).

Example (minimal):
- struct Store<K, M> { repos: HashMap<String, Box<dyn Repository<K, M> + Send>> }

- impl<K, M> Store<K, M> {
    async fn initialize(&mut self) -> Result<()> {
        for name in self.collections.keys().cloned() {
            let repo: &mut dyn Repository<K, M> = self.collection(name).await?;
            // use repo...
        }
        Ok(())
    }
  }

Notes:
- Ensure your struct/impl is generic over K, M: impl<K, M> ...
- If initialize belongs to a different type, also make that type generic over K, M.

Short answer: you can’t initialize repos without knowing the concrete K and M types.

Why:
- collection returns &mut dyn Repository<K, M>, which is tied to specific K, M.
- initialize must exist in a scope where K and M are known (i.e., impl<K, M> or a concrete type).

Options:

1) Make the initialize method generic over K and M (requires the struct/type to be generic over K, M):
- impl<K, M> Store<K, M> {
  async fn initialize(&mut self) -> Result<()> {
    for name in self.collections.keys().cloned() {
      let repo: &mut dyn Repository<K, M> = self.collection(name).await?;
      // use repo...
    }
    Ok(())
  }
}
- This works if your Store is defined as Store<K, M>.

2) If you truly don’t know K, M at compile time, introduce a non-generic wrapper:
- Define a trait object that hides K,M, e.g.:
  trait RepositoryAny {
    fn load_indexes<'a>(&'a mut self) -> Pin<Box<dyn Future<Output=Result<()>> + Send + 'a>>;
  }
- Implement RepositoryAny for all concrete Repository<K, M> you use:
  impl<K, M, T> RepositoryAny for T
  where T: Repository<K, M> + ?Sized { fn load_indexes(&mut self) -> ... { ... } }
- Store Box<dyn RepositoryAny> and have initialize operate on Box<dyn RepositoryAny>.
- Note: you still need a way to produce those trait objects from your collection names.

3) If you only need names and will construct repos one by one later:
- Keep initialize focused on names, then resolve each repo with its concrete K,M when you know them.

In practice, most teams pick option 1 (generic over K, M) and keep the store generic over those params. If you share your exact Store definition (struct and impl bounds), I can tailor the exact snippet.

