Nice. A few concise points and a minimal pattern.

Key ideas:
- Repository is generic over K, M. If you want a trait object, K and M must be fixed for the object.
- Use a concrete Store<K, M> to hold Box<dyn Repository<K, M> + Send + Sync>.
- Async methods in a trait require async_trait (already used).

Minimal pattern:

use async_trait::async_trait;
use std::collections::HashMap;

#[async_trait]
pub trait Repository<K, M>: Send + Sync {
    async fn insert(&mut self, repo: M) -> Result<(), String>;
    async fn delete(&mut self, id: K) -> Result<(), String>;
    async fn find_by_id(&mut self, id: K) -> Option<M>;
    async fn find_all(&mut self) -> Vec<M>;
    async fn update(&mut self, repo: M) -> Result<(), String>;
}

pub struct Store<K, M> {
    repos: HashMap<String, Box<dyn Repository<K, M> + Send + Sync>>,
}

impl<K, M> Store<K, M> {
    pub fn new() -> Self { Self { repos: HashMap::new() } }

    // example: return a mutable repo by name
    pub async fn collection(&mut self, name: String) -> Result<&mut dyn Repository<K, M>, String> {
        self.repos
            .get_mut(&name)
            .map(|r| r.as_mut())
            .ok_or_else(|| "repository not found".into())
    }
}

Notes:
- You must pick concrete K, M when using Store (Store<K, M>).
- If you truly need unknown K/M at compile time, you’ll need a non-generic wrapper around the trait (ephemeral type erasure), which is more involved.

Here’s a minimal concrete example showing a generic Repository<T, U> and a Store<T, U> with a concrete implementation for K = i32, M = String.

use async_trait::async_trait;
use std::collections::HashMap;

// 1) Trait (generic)
#[async_trait]
pub trait Repository<K, M>: Send + Sync {
    async fn insert(&mut self, repo: M) -> Result<(), String>;
    async fn delete(&mut self, id: K) -> Result<(), String>;
    async fn find_by_id(&mut self, id: K) -> Option<M>;
    async fn find_all(&mut self) -> Vec<M>;
    async fn update(&mut self, repo: M) -> Result<(), String>;
}

// 2) Store holding trait objects
pub struct Store<K, M> {
    repos: HashMap<String, Box<dyn Repository<K, M> + Send + Sync>>,
    // optional: names to initialize
    pub collections: Vec<String>,
}

impl<K, M> Store<K, M> {
    pub fn new() -> Self {
        Self {
            repos: HashMap::new(),
            collections: Vec::new(),
        }
    }

    // add a repository
    pub fn add_repo(&mut self, name: String, repo: Box<dyn Repository<K, M> + Send + Sync>) {
        self.repos.insert(name, repo);
    }

    // access by name
    pub async fn collection(&mut self, name: String) -> Result<&mut dyn Repository<K, M>, String> {
        self.repos
            .get_mut(&name)
            .map(|r| r.as_mut())
            .ok_or_else(|| "repository not found".into())
    }
}

// 3) Concrete repo for K = i32, M = String
struct InMemoryRepo {
    data: HashMap<i32, String>,
}

#[async_trait]
impl Repository<i32, String> for InMemoryRepo {
    async fn insert(&mut self, repo: String) -> Result<(), String> {
        let id = self.data.len() as i32 + 1;
        self.data.insert(id, repo);
        Ok(())
    }
    async fn delete(&mut self, id: i32) -> Result<(), String> {
        self.data.remove(&id);
        Ok(())
    }
    async fn find_by_id(&mut self, id: i32) -> Option<String> {
        self.data.get(&id).cloned()
    }
    async fn find_all(&mut self) -> Vec<String> {
        self.data.values().cloned().collect()
    }
    async fn update(&mut self, repo: String) -> Result<(), String> {
        // naive: replace first value
        if let Some((k, _)) = self.data.iter().next() {
            self.data.insert(*k, repo);
        }
        Ok(())
    }
}

// 4) Example usage
#[tokio::main]
async fn main() {
    // create store
    let mut store: Store<i32, String> = Store::new();

    // add a repo
    let repo = InMemoryRepo { data: HashMap::new() };
    store.add_repo("r1".to_string(), Box::new(repo));

    // initialize (example: get repo by name)
    if let Ok(r) = store.collection("r1".to_string()).await {
        // use r, e.g., insert
        let _ = r.insert("doc1".to_string()).await;
        let items = r.find_all().await;
        println!("items: {:?}", items);
    }
}

Notes:
- Store is generic over K, M. You can add more repos and iterate by name.
- If you truly don’t know K, M at compile time, you’ll need a non-generic wrapper (type erasure)—more involved.

Short answer: you can’t call load_indexes() inside the loop while holding the mutable borrow from collection/await. Rust won’t allow a mutable borrow across an await.

Ways to fix (pick one):

Option A — make initialize borrow-free across awaits (use Arc<Mutex<...>>)
- Store repos as Arc<Mutex<Box<dyn Repository<K, M> + Send + Sync>>>
- In initialize, iterate names, grab a clone of the Arc, and spawn/await tasks that lock and call load_indexes().

Example sketch:
- type RepoObj<K,M> = Box<dyn Repository<K,M> + Send + Sync>;
- repos: HashMap<String, Arc<Mutex<RepoObj<K,M>>>>;
- async fn initialize(&mut self) -> Result<()> {
    for name in self.collections.clone() {
      let r = self.repos.get(name).unwrap().clone();
      // spawn or await: lock, call load_indexes, drop lock
      let mut guard = r.lock().await;
      guard.load_indexes().await?;
    }
    Ok(())
  }

Option B — two-phase initialization (no borrow across await)
- Phase 1: collect names (no awaits).
- Phase 2: for each name, obtain the repo, drop borrow, then call load_indexes() in a separate function that takes ownership or a temporary borrow.

Example approach:
- async fn initialize(&mut self) -> Result<()> {
    let names = self.collections.clone();
    for name in names {
      // temporarily borrow to get a &mut dyn Repository, then drop it
      let repo = self.collection(name.clone()).await?;
      // can't call load_indexes here (await borrow issue)
      drop(repo); // drop borrow
      // now load_indexes in a separate step if you have a non-borrowing path
    }
    Ok(())
  }

Option C — consume the store (single-threaded, no borrow across await)
- If you can, design initialize to take ownership of the relevant repos and run load_indexes without another await borrow. This often means changing API so initialize consumes self and repos.

Notes
- If you truly need to keep repos generic and unknown at compile time, you’ll need a non-generic wrapper or a concurrency-safe wrapper (e.g., Arc<Mutex<...>>) to allow awaiting without holding a borrow across await.
- Otherwise, move load_indexes into a non-async method and spawn a task per repo.

If you share how your Store currently stores repos (hash map type, and whether you’re okay with Arc/Mutex), I can give a tiny, concrete snippet.
